Very highly recommended restaurant here in our region! I went to this restaurant to taste their bestseller food. I thanked the waitress for serving the food hot. I was so satisfied with the taste and the price. You really got my taste, guys! You expect me to eat here again! Cheers for the delicious food!

We were there (unplanned) for the Game of Thrones menu. The links to the show felt a bit forced, but the food was generally very good. Service was incredibly friendly and informative. We will definitely be back. Some courses worked better than others, but the overall sense was that of fine dining on a lower key scale. The room is small and the decorations are charming. Steak cooked perfectly, sides of a good portion and overall quality, and excellent desserts.

At the moment  you come to this restaurant  they give you a comfortable feeling. Very comfortable waiters, it is a good restaurant to  pass time with friends or with your date. delightful  cooking, specialist  chef, decent  price and excellent  service. Warmly recommended.

We've been going to Elizabeth for 6 years. The menu is always delicious and creative, the atmosphere is relaxed and unpretentious and we love the staff! Highly recommended!

I go to this special restaurant from time to time since I enjoy the special air that is unique to this place. The team is very cordial and qualified. The service is deeply efficient. Not to mention, the food they cook is highly distinguished. I frequent often and I was always joyful. The expense is reasobable. I highly suggest this place to to all.
Absolutely amazing blend of understated décor, friendly knowledgeable staff, and delicious and often surprising food. Loved it!

We had an amazing dinner for the Star Wars themed special!  The restaurant was purposefully decorated with outer space and movie themed memorabilia, and even the music was space themed!  The food was divine.  The explanations and the connections to the Star Wars canon made the whole evening fun.  My wife has grown tired of my pure excitement since Rise of Skywalker was released, but even she appreciated the fresh look at the stories.  Your team is incredibly talented and courteous.  Chef Regan made sure we had enough paired drinks so that we could fully enjoy the menu as she intended.  This was our first time doing a non-alcoholic pairing, and it was truly a home-run.  Thank you for a wonderful evening.
I prefer this venue a lot. there is a friendly air. The kitcen is exeptionaly good. the service is efficient and the waiters are friendly. The price is modest. truly recommend.

Bold, nuanced dishes and nicely paired drinks, all presented with wit and flair. Themed nights provide whimsy and charm (and a challenge for wait staff trying to remember how the food connects) but an equal amount of effort seems to have gone into creating a space that celebrates the experience of dining out. Maybe the most enjoyable meal out I've had in the twenty plus years I've lived in Chicago.

Just completed a standard tasting menu at Elizabeth. For over $1000 total we completed a wine and tasting pairing for 2. The dinner was disorganized. At the completion we were presented with a menu that did not reflect the foods and wines we were given yet we were changed exorbitant prices. I would not return nor recommend. Steer clear unless you enjoy paying inflated prices for minimal food at ridiculous prices.
Fantastic experience!

I like this place, the grilled fish so good. The staff are welcoming to everyone. Nice service and the owner he is wonderful. I’m happy to dining at this place every weekend.

We visited Elizabeth- chef Iliana Regan's masterpiece named after her deceased sister, in February 2016. The featured menu was the Winter menu. Regan is self taught chef (She holds a degree in Fiction Writing) but has worked at some of the best restaurants in Chicago, including Alina. Elizabeth is a single small rectangular room with seating for about 20 people and a completely open kitchen as part of the dining room. This creates an almost too intimate setting - one almost doesn't want to talk too loud so as to not disturb the chefs. Making up for most of this awkwardness is the service staff, who were kind, knowledgeable and very personable.

This place is quite literally the best. I went during the downtown abbey menu season. My SO booked it and paid-- I've since read that it's very expensive, so I'm not quite sure about the value since I am still unaware of the actual cost. That being said, it was the best meal of my life. I tried things I didn't even think I'd be able to keep down (apparently fois gras is DELISH)! It was a wonderful experience. The chefs were fun to watch, the servers all very informative. If you can, try to put this on the list.

Elizabeth is hands down my favorite restaurant in Chicago and possibly the world.  As amazing an experience you get at the likes of Alinea, the meal is a more enjoyable experience at Elizabeth - I truly feel welcome when I dine at Elizabeth and have since my first time there.  I will happily venture to Elizabeth 8-10 times a year and will not miss a menu if I can at all help it.  Every dish at Elizabeth is to die for, from starter to dessert and their bread course is without fail the one I would repeat every time if such an option existed!  I have taken a number of friends here and not one was disappointed in the slightest!

Very unique restaurant.

One of my favorite restaurants in Chicago. This Michelin starred restaurant offers a variety of tasting menus based on serious to whimsical themes and then some casual small menus on various weeknights. From Game of Thrones menus to Wes Anderson to Julia Child and Vegan, the menu changes and offers some interesting story telling in the form of cuisine.
Good food

Elizabeth is hands down my favorite restaurant in Chicago. Or is it hands up? 🙌 Chef Iliana Regan has a completely unique and original vision for her food and it shines. Each dish is masterfully composed and purposeful with a clear narrative, almost like a brilliant short story. You’ll definitely have a great experience no matter which menu you choose to go to, but the pop culture themed ones like ‘Harry Potter’ or ‘Game of Thrones’ are probably the most fun.

Inventive menu, wonderful service, and the courses were well timed. We had the Harry Potter themed menu, which was fun. The presentations were great and most of the flavors worked really well together - the only thing I wasn't really fond of was the uni, which was extremely potent. Overall, quite enjoyable. Could have used just a little more food - I wasn't starving after like I have been with some tasting menus but I did come home and have a snack.
A touch expensive, but the whimsical experience was definitely worth going.
So creative and fun - love the staff and the food here!

Went for the Wicked Wizard dinner and was blown away by the service, the food, the atmosphere, and the patience of the staff in dealing with my obnoxious self. Table 3 was lit and so was my entire experience here ❤️

Here for the Wicked and Wild School of Wizardly Wonder (Harry Potter themed) menu. I was told by my dining companion and HP fanatic that a couple of dishes had some deep cuts that were straight from the books.  Weaving these influences into the menu while maintaining the restaurants concept of local and foraged worked brilliantly and deliciously.  The intimate setting (about 10 2 tops) was a very comfortable dining experience as the kitchen was very much part or the dining space and made for fascinating viewing between each of the 13 courses.
Great food and nice ambience. Will definitely recommend this place to everyone. 5 stars.

It's easy to see why this place has a Michelin star. Everything about the place kind of plays on a central theme. The decor, the food, the staff all kind of add to the vibe. The food is obviously of a high caliber and was executed with great care. It's not always satisfying the way you might be used to with a conventional restaurant but it's always interesting and certainly unique. Definitely reflects the skill of the chef and the ingredients are often foraged, which is a huge huge plus for me. Definitely recommend trying at least once, especially if you are into experiencing high level fine dining.
Always have interesting food here, I am tempted to move to Chicago so I can try all the seasonal menus.

Great experience. Very enjoyable variety in a 6 course dinner. Their bread is really amazing... Don't gloss over it at the beginning of your meal. Since the menu changes often all I can say is the food is  interesting, flavorful and very we prepared. If you can and it's your thing, definitely sit at a table by the kitchen. Watching food being prepared really heightened the fun of it for us. Wine pairings were discernably sensible for two people with no knowledge of wine. On the night we went each staff member brought out a dish and described it - it was really neat to kind of meet each person. A few notes. First: yes they are happy to accept tips. Not super clear for this kind of place. If you're a ticketed reservation novice like us there's the answer for this place. Second it was not clear coffee was not included in the price... A little annoying to get a bill for coffee but not really a big deal. Last there's no apparent dress code. Showed up in Friday work business casual with a backpack and no issues. Totally recommend overall.

(Translated by Google) Valuing each of the ingredients that goes into the dish is the proposal of the wonderful restaurant by chef Iliana Regan! Keeping its Michelin star since 2014, the restaurant offers a seasonal tasting menu with the best of American food (forget about junkie food, we are talking about real food). When you arrive, the façade can even scare you a little and it is difficult to see it written in the door in small letters "Elizabeth". The environment is a delight and consists of only 9 tables where you can see the intense activity of a silent kitchen in which the smell of the dishes being prepared with so many herbs and spices makes the restaurant have a friendly home atmosphere.  The menu costs USD 80.00 and is already paid at the time of booking, which can be done online without any problem. After the experience they send you the menu you tasted to find out exactly what each dish was. The space is an excellent option for vegetarians, but it also offers some meat dishes. The dishes may seem simple, but they are super elaborated to bring the basic ingredients to life.  The size of the portions is deceiving and you definitely won't go hungry, not least because I don't know if I was lucky, but in my case they offered some extra blacks as a courtesy, making my experience at Elizabeth even better! :)  The fact is: once in Chicago, schedule to go to Elizabeth! You will not regret!  (Original) Valorizar cada um dos ingredientes que vai para o prato é a proposta do maravilhoso restaurante da chef Iliana Regan! Mantendo sua estrela Michelin desde 2014 o restaurante oferece um menu degustação sazonal com o melhor da comida americana (esqueça o junkie food, estamos falando de comida de verdade). O ambiente é uma delicia e está composto de apenas 9 mesas de onde se pode ver a atividade intensa de uma cozinha silenciosa na qual o cheiro dos pratos sendo preparados com tantas ervas e temperos faz o restaurante ter um clima de casa de amigo.  O menu custa USD 80,00 e já é pago no momento da reserva, que pode ser feita online sem nenhum problema. Após a experiência eles enviam pra você o cardápio que você degustou para saber exatamente o que era cada prato. O espaço é uma excelente opção pata vegetarianos, mas também oferece alguns pratos com carne. Os pratos podem parecer simples, mas são super elaborados para dar vida aos ingredientes básicos.  O tamanho das porções engana e definitivamente você não sairá com fome, até porque não sei se tive sorte, mas no meu caso ofereceram alguns pretos extras como cortesia, deixando a minha experiência no Elizabeth ainda melhor! :)  O fato é: uma vez em Chicago, se programe para ir ao Elizabeth! Você não vai se arrepender!

A special experience, in a atmosphere that I really enjoyed. The place definitely has the look and feel of your childhood living room, which might not be for everyone but I liked. The food is outstanding, but especially the beer/wine pairing is fantastic - we had both and I was amazed how often the beer had the same character as the wine, and fit the food perfectly. The wine was more whites, but also a bit of red, champagne and even a sparkling rose that was outstanding. Their cocktail selection of a few interpretations of classics is astonishing. The Downton Abbey had more seafood than I understand is typically their thing (and not mine), but I ate everything, even the salmon, which is a huge testament to how good it was.

I have visited Elizabeth twice in 8 days, first for a Sunday brunch then for a Sunday night family dinner.  To borrow heavily from my dining companion's words: I could go on and on about all the reasons why I love this place. The food is always delicious. The energy is unpretentious but still at a level of class that is so dignified. It's clear that Iliana Regan is not only a stellar chef but a humble leader who empowers those around her. She is a genuinely good person who has never lost her passion for food, sees the raw power in bringing people together over a meal and who has a team around her that embodies all the values she demonstrates. During brunch a week back Iliana took time out from the open air kitchen to greet guests.  Her team never left our coffee mugs cold, and graciously fielded question after question about the delights we were eating, being so patient with our child like wonder. Last night's menu was created by one of the chefs on Regan's team; highlighting Southeast Asian street food and inspired by his year spent living in a rural town outside of Laos. The flavors were bold, pungent and spicy. His food was the star of the night. liana washed dishes! One of the FOH staff shared stories about her kids. Tonya ran outside, into the frigid cold, to make sure we didn't forget a mini to-go bag...it was perfect. Thank you for reminding us that there is a community of people who stand for something with no compromises in execution of their art.

The food, the wine and the staff at Elizabeth are overflowing with a natural and honest charm.  Also, I've never had a better slice of homemade long fermented sourdough bread in my entire life.   Eat here.   This place is special.
Fantastic "Tasting" brunch.  Great food and great service.

Absolutely amazing dining experience. Regan is a wonderfully passionate chef and you can absolutely see the results through her food. The restaurant itself is very cozy and intimate. Staff is always a treat and the dining experiences for each season/menu are as varied as they are wonderful.

Every menu here is fabulous. Get tickets to anything. Elizabeth Restaurant is where Modernist meets wild foraged. The dishes are a parade of eye-candy that display intelligence, whimsy, and a deep understanding of ingredients and their terrior.  The dishes are not merely beautiful, they are deeply satisfying. I’ve had the most sumptuous slices of waygu at Elizabeth. One course was comprised of a pear-sized whole deep fried Hen of the Woods mushroom that I cut apart with a steak knife and of which I savored every bite. It was the most delicious thing I’ve ever eaten.  Chef Iliana Regan plays with contrasting temperatures in the most wonderful way. She also includes seemingly bizarre elements from nature, like Spruce tips and edible moss, the pickled roots of cattails, or tender legs of frogs she captured herself (fresh!). These wild items are not gimmicks. Rather, they pack powerful flavor and excitement. I requested seconds on a Spruce tip soda. Seriously, where has Spruce been all my life? The flavor is amazing!  One especially nice new opportunity at Elizabeth Restaurant is the truly excellent brunches and Casual Sunday dinners that one can find tickets for on the restaurant’s web site. These wonderful meal options make Chef Regan’s wonderful vibe and brilliant cooking accessible to a broader (largely blue jean-wearing) clientele. Those seeking fancy food should stick to Elizabeth Restaurant’s dinner series. Brunch won’t feature uni and foam, but it does sometimes feature wonderful, seasonal wild mushrooms, the chef’s award-worthy bread, house made preserves, magically delicious eggs, house made bacon and other treats, my favorite of which are the Bunny the Bakery whisky-glazed donuts. Best donuts ever!  I particularly love the service at Elizabeth. The entire staff seems to emit a peaceful, bright, engaging resonance and operate from a sophisticated awareness of how to set the tone for each interaction.  This incredible restaurant and its brilliant chef earn my highest recommendation.

In the dining room at Downton Abbey, opulent jewels decorate the décolletages of Lord and Lady Grantham’s three lovely daughters. At Elizabeth Restaurant’s "Downton Abbey" Dinner Series, the courses themselves are the jewels!  The wine was really flowing when we visited Elizabeth Restaurant for the amazing "Downton Abbey" Dinner Series, Servants vs. Aristocrats. The pours were particularly generous with this wonderful menu, which seemed appropriate when celebrating the lives of the aristocratic Crawley family and their domestic servants in the post-Edwardian era.  While I was a huge fan of the show, you don’t need to have ever watched “Downton Abbey” to enjoy this menu enormously. With courses like Salmon Caviar, Pickled Squash and King Crab on Iliana Regan’s famous house made bread, the menu does not need to tie directly to the show, as the stunningly beautiful courses are fascinating and sumptuous beyond compare. I have loved many of Elizabeth Restaurant’s menus, but this one is my favorite yet!  With such incredibly fine ingredients, I found this menu to be an excellent value for the price. The "Thermidor" of Charred Langoustine with Pickled Rose” was my favorite course. I also loved the unique mushrooms, including matsutake and enoki. They play a prominent role in this menu and are, of course, cooked to perfection. The “Foie Gras and Dry Aged Beef with Fermented Berry, and Buckwheat” are seducing me back for another dinner while this menu lasts.  Chef Iliana Regan is a James Beard Best Chef nominee and winner of Food and Wine Best New Chef. Elizabeth Restaurant’s well-deserved Michelin star shines brightly through this exquisite menu. As long as tickets are available, you will not want to miss this menu.

I just jumped on the Elizabeth Restaurant website and grabbed tickets to Downton Abbey for a second visit. We had so much fun with the Downton Abbey menu that I absolutely have to experience it again. One of my guests had never seen the show and she enjoyed dinner just as much as we did. Being a fan of the PBS hit “Downton Abbey” is not essential to enjoying this important menu.  Can a dinner be important? Yes, I think this one can. The Downton Abbey menu is decisively my favorite Elizabeth Restaurant menu ever. The brilliance of Iliana Regan, is that she is an impressionist chef who never replicates dishes, but rather deconstructs and rebirths them as something entirely different. The heirloom dishes become a theme, more so than a model for her. Her creations generally far exceed the appeal of what she’s riffing on, and herein lies her culinary and artistic magic.  Impressionist painting includes visible brush strokes, inclusion of movement as a crucial element of perception, and unusual visual angles. This is what I mean when I say that Iliana Regan is an impressionist chef. The menu is a blend of traditional and unique elements, but everything is translated through her unique and beautiful way of creating. For instance, the foie gras with vegetable crudités is served in her signature style reminiscent of Bunny the Bakery’s famous Foie Gras Owls on a bed of what can only be described as a superbly beautiful garden of vegetables so fresh and delicious that one notices how truly beautiful their textures and forms are.  I also booked something new that I haven’t tried before. Elizabeth Restaurant now has “Casual Sundays” where they serve family-style. These meals feature entrees like friend chicken, fish fry, or a whole roasted pig. I read that the friend chicken pop-ups that Chef Regan hosted last year were amazing and I was very sad that I had missed them. I just bought tickets for three Casual Sundays to increase my odds of catching a fried chicken night.  I also came for brunch recently and need to come back soon. The crust on the homemade sourdough was amazing and I’m watching for another bread-making class to arise, so that I can learn the secret behind Elizabeth Restaurant’s bread.

Hurry! Book tickets for the Downton Abbey menu. It's the best I’ve ever had. This dinner packed more excitement than Lady Mary and her lovers. The courses were too generous and numerous to write about them all, so I'll review only a few. The amuse blew my mind and I knew it was only up from there. “Crisp Bread, Salmon Caviar and Pickled Squash with King Crab and Candied Lemon” burst with flavor in my mouth. The next course was a perfect oyster with dashi that made me never want to eat an oyster without dashi again. This is the melding of flavors that will have me craving dashi on every oyster forever. The “Dry Aged Beef with Fermented Berry and Buckwheat” was amazing on its sourdough bread. I would make this my last meal. The “Stuffed Swiss Chard with House made Bacon, Minnesota Wild Rice, Pumpkin, and Sunflower” was such a lovely contrast to the dry aged beef.  Chef Iliana Regan is most certainly a genius. This is the fifth menu I’ve enjoyed at Elizabeth and truly, the restaurant keeps besting itself. The Downton Abbey menu is magnificent from start to finish. The “Yorkshire Pudding With Rose Petal Ice Cream, Cured Egg Yolk and Rose Oil” would have pleased even Aunt Violet and softened her tough exterior. As a beekeeper, the “Profiterole with Bee Pollen Ice Cream and Pickled Pear” is my favorite dessert of all times.  This menu was a trip through the richness of Downton Abbey, but it’s clear that Mrs. Patmore could not have ever engineered such finery. This exquisite menu, the best I’ve ever had, could happen only at Elizabeth Restaurant.
Amazing brunch, perfect pairings, and just wait for the donut.

Very good and creative dishes. Our theme was "ugly fruits" (which changes every few months) and vegetable/fruit-centric.  However, nothing was ugly at all - and all delicious.   The space is very small and very casual, although the service was fairly formal and comprehensive.

Buy tickets in advance and do the wine or beer pairing. Her classes and outings are a must do as well.
Fantastic, magical experience. Artful food, wonderful service, makes for a special evening for sure.

Might not be the place for you if you are a soulless vampire incapable of feeling joy or love. However, if you have a pulse and warmth in your heart it will be impossible for you not to feel lifted and delighted by your experience at this amazing establishment. The talent and the devotion to quality is shadowed only by the presentation and care taken in making sure your evening is pleasurable.

Elizabeth presents a multi-course dining experience, with all the foods being very seasonal.   The dishes are tailored to the season, and are presented in interesting molecular gastronomy manners.   The centerpiece usually contains something edible, as well presentations may involve a terrarium.   There are wine pairings available, and the staff will let you split a tasting among 2 diners.   A must-dine for the gourmands in Chicago.

A phenomenal dinner. Tiny intense burst of flavor from small foraged flowers, herbs, berries (nightshade, queen anne's lace, fennel pollen, and other flowers) on top of a range of creative dishes each highlighting a few ingredients (malted barley, beets, bear, tomatoes, roe). We were also lucky enough to get to sit right next to the kitchen watching everything come together. Bravo!
Just delightful. Charming space and some of the best most incentive food I've had the pleasure of trying in a long time. The standout for me was the fried hen of the woods mushroom.

I believe this is the best dining experience in Chicago.  Imagine combining the creativity of Alinea with the "tastiness" of Schwa in an environment which is all about the food.  Creativity was amazing with such dishes as bear, edible dirt, sea urchin all suprising with twists and turns which almost play out in a  playful narrative.

Chef Iliana Regan's food has the magical presence of Mother Nature mixed with creativity and peppered with molecular techniques. It kept my mouth happy and my taste buds jumping for joy with anticipation for the next course. It's fine dining food and service in a comfortable environment. Highly recommend this restaurant!

Gorgeous intricate delicious food in an welcoming and beautiful setting. I strongly suggest the deer menu, which showcases the unique style of the chef, which is a blend of Midwest, Kaiseki, and a tinge of New Nordic.
